The Higgs boson dissected
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly certain.
Suppose it is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this low world, a inevitably inevitable law that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break this rule – and don’t try too hard, you’re going to hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary) The Particle Adventure site, from the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "particles of force", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all beasts as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that precise location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond, only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Indeed, not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold of itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, hold) do not.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between MS observations and predictions.
In fact, there are many who fervently wish that one finds it, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and block some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (ops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (re-ops!).
But no such deviations have been found at CERN until now.
Impacts
The repercussions of this research on the daily life of Monsieur and Madame Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser technology at Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution their work was about to unleash.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - already told us that initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Just imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intent, now serves as an "eye" to all the digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die... <0x7C> Duty
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, in this essential area, much remains to be done.
The Duty tried to take a closer look at it.
Only a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The cancer of the prostate that was eating him had left him a respite of two years.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," says he, half fig half grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for it," he said.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Nestled in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is that I get cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he confides.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"Throughout our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Returning to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a life expectancy of up to three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and suffocated."
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she added.
"I don't have any more wishes in life," she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she expects a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, we provide body care and food assistance.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will agree to provide mouth care for brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, a beer was served to Mr. X, who died overnight.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, well-kept in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel worries.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in the nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that makes several doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care boards including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients ask to die only because they don't get the right care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard’s hopes for survival were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
But she told me I was done!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not acceding to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping the patient until the time of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
