With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is the opposite of current central bank-based currency exchanges, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning today to around a dozen dollars (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
Yet the European Central Bank (ECB) has been interested in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competitive with the dollar or euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as “credits”, used to progress in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes trade in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, every time, a central authority controls and handles the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes in the network are both bookkeepers, verifiers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public account book, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge for computers, and the winner, sort of a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a file hash phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving some margin.
The difficulty of the challenge is also met with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
“The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this defect.
Major players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant sales” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come back cheaper.
The wearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the U.S. are expected to follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them as terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the mutilated.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse foreign military presence, as in the days of the Soviets.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, they will no longer be when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was done in order.
Convoys of trucks and armoured vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflew by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban surge in Kabul as of the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country on fire and bloody as a result of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved nowadays.
Former Mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban join in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land to sell it as building land to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracts.
They disregarded themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to take advantage of American bounties: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They sided with the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they enjoyed the benefits of it.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, government schools are full, both girls and boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of some leaders.
All, including armed opponents, are fond of mobile phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas that feature a modern world, are followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities that are going to command it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already concerned with rebuilding provincial militias, which will escape the central power.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some decentralization, like Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state with strong presidential power, abolishing the post of Prime Minister that existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially in the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been, since the 1950s and long before, dependent on foreign aid.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in repair, no major irrigation systems are repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruits and vegetables.
Priority is left to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There was a rumor that Afghanistan possessed immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that the Westerners were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore on site, nor means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the copper mine of Mes Aynak, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to search the huge Buddhist site and remain the province’s most important employers.
It will also take a day for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports are largely dependent, to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: high school for girls, boys, French department at university, French institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to achieve the impossible task of making aid and offensive actions coincide, a "civil-military actions" department of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has conducted, and carried out by a small French NGO, numerous collective work and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
This work, which requires local labor, was able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of arable land.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much smaller budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, which are often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, as I have been told by farmers to wish, small, well-controlled and direct civilian aid would have to be maintained in their favour.
A Constitution with a forceps in Egypt
This is President Mohammed Morsi's new poker move.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this Assembly two more months to finish its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, several times amended, which undermines institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only widened the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "trampling the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor, as he said in an interview with the US weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote holds the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the vast majority Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they could not make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were hurriedly added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, most of the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators have also been amused that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, with some members of the committee believing that the constituent's clock was poorly regulated.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Article 2 remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the Liberals respond, who see it only as a communication blow.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system "tempers Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from the religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another issue: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military tribunals be prohibited, as demanded by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
Blasphemy is maintained and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women anymore, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has chosen five great reasons to travel to Israel.
Go to worship the holy places
A must-see event: the banks of the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptism grounds” will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was in this very place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the praetorium), where the trial took place, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
It is here that the Christian center of the world is located, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wailing Wall, which constitutes the remainder of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave little words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Massada Fortress, a former refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs claim that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (the parliament).
It houses the ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also to see: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It exhibits mainly the paintings of the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Al-Basha Hammam awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of castings of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which revisits the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not drop below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Blue-colored water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
They come to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, healing sludge and to cure various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who have come to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk around with high air.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be enjoyed.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists traveled to the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists controversy over what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already made their appearance in the country
Each year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are Central Asian nationals: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to make money to help their families staying at home.
Since December 1, a law has entered into force that stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
At the moment, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or diplomas of education before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have already asked the press many times: what will it do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many are talking about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they are taken their passports, and they do not receive the planned salary," said Tolib Sharipov, the head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, policeman!
However, many Central Asian nationals who wish to make money in Russia trust that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to visit, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach their teenage years, these young people make money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will only be for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have fake documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Oumed Khouchkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
"Make it quick, don't let it down and buy yourself a beautiful work of art."
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be fake.
Several fake language exam certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of exams had to pay 7,000 rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power officials and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “tips of paper.”
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the first exam time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low.
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is proposing to tighten the law against civilian weapons bearers.
This is the reaction of the authorities in the face of recent incidents: whether it be the shootings at weddings or the killing organised by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for gun licences from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma’s Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced at the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is pleased to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter has appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168,000 crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening laws on civilian weapons will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the dissemination of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking commands of weapons
The first is "military trace", that is, weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often been subjected to explosions.
"Attested reports indicate that some fires were deliberately set off to cover up the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private arms factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” one expert said.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A significant share of pistols and machine guns came from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons in the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers say, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the guns on the black market have been found there "due to the fault of employees whose work is related to guns," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "illegal searches".
A salesman and consultant at an armory who asked to remain anonymous says that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these specialists in the clandestine search; they are too old.
Most often, he says, sellers will pick up new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT pistol.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
"He transports it to the city and sells it for 900 € per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a check purchase from illegal arms dealers," the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I checked sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone had to take me to a "coin" to bargain.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, says the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust them.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you also have to come and say, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them.
The little ones are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, he said, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want."
“I thought I was in a luxury store,” recalls the soldier.
There is no secret for the buyer, Baranets explains, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I'm not just buying, we go with the seller in the forest and we set up a target.
“I’m allowed to shoot and when I’m convinced the gun works well, we start negotiating,” he said.
A shop from the couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, we do not need any documents and no one to meet.
"It is enough to have a precise amount of money," the advertisement reads on the site "Buy a gun or a machine gun."
Users leave their request and ask questions.
And we sell to miners?
"Without permission, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (orthography preserved).
"Buy TT. Moscow," writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has spread a huge network of fake sites and picks up people who want to buy combat weapons.
