U.S.: Fast Food and Supermarket Employees Strike
Nearly a quarter of American teenagers go through a cashier's job at McDonald's
In recent days, a wave of protests has risen against low wages by Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave is going to grow or breathe out quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Along with the increase in modest wages for basic employees at Walmart and in fast food chains, the organizers of the demonstrations want the creation of unions.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday," as a surging rain of salaries seizing millions of people hit America and sometimes sparking outcry.
On that day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize pickets of strikes with unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores whose products are intended for consumers of the modest and middle classes.
Walmart markets everything from diapers to hunting rifles to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paying employees at Walmart shop only at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply because of the low wages of its employees.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded a salary increase, complaining that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For the basic employee at Walmart who gets $9.5 an hour, that's an amount he can't afford.
Scientists at California University of Berkley show that if Walmart raised the average salary to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That’s 1.1% more than it currently spends.
If Walmart were to transfer all the wage increases on the shoulders of consumers, every run in the store would be 46 cents more.
They will spend $12.39 more in a year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8 am in the evening to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over that period 5,000 items per second.
His coffers made a total of 100 million transactions for "Black Friday".
A spokesperson for the company Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post that “less than five” Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was just a “com’ operation among many” on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
The protests continued this week in New York and were not about Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not very popular, which is why they are not there yet) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s advertises selling billions of servings and then they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you’ve done honestly!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, the minimum wage provided by federal and New York legislation is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food grows over time, but on average, its core employees in New York City earn $8.90 an hour.
No one touches less than them in this city.
It is inconceivable for me to live with this sum in New York.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald's after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live with this salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the Wall Street Journal forum there are comments saying that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know what you are going to feed them.
The protesters who launched the move Thursday at 6.30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and fast-food cooks be paid at least $15 an hour, a multiplication of more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing union protesters with bullying or dismissal.
However, administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a union, seizing fast food remains a difficult task, and that for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary staff turnover.
They don't agree
Other tumultuous protests were held near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the mid-day rally near Times Square's McDonald's with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's announcement sells billions of servings and then they don't even give you sick leave and don't pay you for the job you've done honestly!"
The protesters were backed by other prominent New York Democrats, including mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio who said, “We all need to support fast food workers so they get a fair salary and the economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times characterized the event as the most important event in the fast food industry in its entire history.
But only a few hundred people participated, not to mention that not all of them were fast food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is currently difficult to say whether this spark of mass movement will make small ones.
"At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain."
Recently, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it emerges from the interview with the director of the interactive 3D technology group of the Microsoft lab in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment with flat screen pixels and sometimes with touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead of us and guess the radical changes that will happen with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox sells today without Kinect because everyone is interested in controlling by gesture.
- What does the future hold for us too?
- Although the Kinect made the physical interaction, a lot of things take place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The information entry has been improved (the system receives more data), but the performance, for the moment, is not really.
We're trying to change that and we're working on truly 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We must bring the computer world out into our own, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds it.
Thus, we will be able to complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And to begin with, let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command?
It is appreciated, but isn’t it overestimated?
One cannot say that it is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of his actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera, but by a hand-held bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or can't do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don't you like about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we rely in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but rather the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all the current technologies are quite good, this adds work to the algorithm designers.
It is necessary to keep in mind the resolution according to the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond lab, gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 <0xCE><0xBC>s, with the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device like that in my work, but not needing to touch, to have more frames per second.
- But shouldn't we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect today has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a reflective signal receiver.
And the third camera is actually a usual sensor of the visible field.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem.
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, play with the curve of the cameras and see how it could help define the locations.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most perspectives?
- Of course, walking all the time with a smartphone with your hands raised is not convenient but here is what I think: the best option would be an augmented reality "transient" that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch glasses to the smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and this is what makes them strong (personal elements are the only ones you see) and at the same time weak: Augmented reality from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem that opponents of this idea point to: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing!
What responses does your group prepare to this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
For the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image medium.
It perfectly records the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are actually meant to assign palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a precise point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of your fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also an axis of work presenting perspectives.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
Make him believe that he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
There’s still a task below that will take a long time to work on: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that they are walking in an open space that is almost infinite – we are working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there are still many years of work left.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
