Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Climate warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with earthlings on board set out in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a planet of relief?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"These are Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If the conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the surface temperature of Venus is 500.
We can only live there at very high altitude or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from earthly varieties.
Then insects, small breeding Drosophila flies were put into orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how an embryo developed into weightlessness.
We get a perfectly normal chick at the exit.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its feet and start moving," says Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
When no support was found, the chicks stirred in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophied.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We squinted their eyes twice and then gave up, because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature arch" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, reproductions have not yet been made directly in space.
It's not a small deal.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, man is capable, in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thought, it is capable of creating a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the robbery.
“No one was answering that question,” says Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a retired rocket and space veteran.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The father of the child, Andrian Nikolaev was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, having been in orbit twice and even worked in an extravehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk remains.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbital flights," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valery Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology laboratory of the Centre for the preparation of cosmonauts: obligatory stage of the preparation for flight.
Here, in zero buoyancy, the cosmonauts train for extra-vehicle exits.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their real element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby evolves about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's belly, it is easier for him to get used to water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from birth until its first bath, it only happens 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on the birth simulators.
One can of course prepare a childbirth in a special room, the woman will manage to get him out.
"And then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite reflection on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the earthly attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
An infant cannot be dressed as an adult with a special training suit.
It will simply be deprived of its vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case by imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will lead to the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely misfit," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, when the Earthlings will travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their offspring born in space.
