At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German draft in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was it specifically about?
This is a parallel check that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, EU legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and practice itself.
We have put all this together and although this control procedure is not yet complete, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more stringent and of better quality", nevertheless, by some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to continuously develop more and more detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote oneself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it result for you?
Such a common oversight should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, lower and improve the thresholds, when it does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
