Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern Bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on spaceflights; they did not always meet understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The said doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a draught was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press at the time.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The evidence in the records indicates that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and as early as the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM weather rocket (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
An upgraded version, RM-1A, was subsequently built and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were initiated in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket was developed between 1962 and 1965 and succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B that volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautics Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of the program.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Service Works Act.
This decision has sparked a lively discussion in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This concretely means that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with one another.
This results from the principle of freedom of trade and free (unlimited) movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wage) generate a tension on prices.
The following meaning must be given to this term: a producer strives by importing goods sold at low prices to resist economic competition by "making" the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of taking away a greater share of the market and thus increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, or buy at low prices, or disappear. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the state's social charges necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so publicly known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments are putting their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard to social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to economically compel its own population to accept the dictate of the prices of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is achieved on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand by the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is increasing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years, who cannot provide for themselves with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted by millions.
In the context of the increased competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay an extra to reach the minimum living wage.
For example, such a scandal has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live on miserable wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will be invested in their country.
The question is, where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media say, tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, and even does not today, according to its own selfish interests, govern politics and, by the same token, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of bills to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills were then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as the Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is evident that liberalist-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his work entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state was long in decline and functions were attributed by violence.
Bribes, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-table and the corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with already sold votes"... ... "The honest people did not seek at all to obtain functions, it resulted once the state was transformed 8 months without consuls".... ' It really began to be said that the remedy for this difficult situation was an autocracy, but that it was "absolutely necessary" to choose a man n...
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of elites, with no effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today's elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repealing the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution, at least not in the long run.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at the international and at the internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase citizens' influence on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
