'Mark Protection' in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing the trade mark's name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd win the case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a workbook containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by taking over part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the champions of the world of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: his constituents task him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is by this term that women are designated who marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch says.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to the data of the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the third world market for luxury products and the fastest growing.
However, it is not easy to erase dubious trademark registrations and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch mentions the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long time, the denomination criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay the plagiarism money because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, the purchaser of Volvo, used before a blue and white logo reminiscent of that of BMW. The conflict was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to the Hong Kong and Singapore plagiarists who had redirected the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the Trademark Office of CTMO in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year, the office would have changed from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a regained normality".
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have fallen by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases would have been closed, representing a 75% increase from the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Acting is Expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the OTMC received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
According to the Office, this is a record and means that China is in the top spot for the tenth time in a row for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fee.
In other words, each record earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarism.
Certainly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components to be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"It's our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office had therefore rejected the objection of the Munich residents.
Freudenberg won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "The procedure is lengthy, exhausting and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives Service has even had to review the acts of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party in vain a "large six-digit euro sum" to settle the dispute.
“This is what it means to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region ensured the exploitation of the unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to deposit the name Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Vigilanty is required."
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, they say, to rely on international trademark law, but foreigners should "also register in China everything that is likely to be protected," as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or else we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
