During Mubarak's reign, these courts tried to repress opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held by the military.
The state must also protect "the true nature of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morality and values".
From a legal point of view, the wording is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematography and literature.
It would simply be censorship.
In addition, no article expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offense is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording suggesting that it is forbidden to "offend persons".
Is it enough to draw a caricature of the president or tell a joke to the detriment of a lawyer?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft that Morsi puts to the vote and that, in his own words, will "very soon" be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The Revolution is Reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday evening, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in an unusual concord in Tahrir Square in Cairo, promising to bring down the Sharia before it comes into force.
"The revolution is reborn and we will win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, who was third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is “to be thrown into the trash cans of history.”
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to foment a “coup against democracy.”
“If he proclaims the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow it,” said Jasser Said, an opponent.
“We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned,” said Khaled Ali, a politician and member of the opposition.
In addition, several judges have announced that they do not want to monitor the referendum, which would lead to its nullity.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim Brotherhood called for a counter-demonstration not on Tahrir Square as a precautionary measure, but on the other side of the Nile, where a large prayer was organized in front of the University of Cairo.
The veiled women and supporters of the Salafists, who participated in large numbers, chanted: "The people demand the application of the law of God."
“Clean up our country!” they asked Morsi, claiming that “the Qur’an [was their] Constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty on the symbolic Tharir Square, where everything began, would soon have generated a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, this is what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said opponents of the draft constitution, like its supporters, had spoken loudly.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide by the ballot box which direction the country should take.
The Islamists’ project will certainly win the majority.
“Human rights are not mentioned once”
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process that should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood while in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their view of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That is why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now, the term is not even pronounced once in the new Constitution," he said during his interview with Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will create a new dictatorship in Egypt.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto takes away all of his powers,” Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, which looks at the battle between different political ideologies on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
That could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: “You are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control.”
Norway’s Rakfisk: Is it the world’s most fragrant fish?
The five million people living in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret to the country’s success be tied to the locals’ appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet, dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most prized dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this ubiquitous smell permeates the air.
Rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness sets in and it’s cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw and then you swallow a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a local full-time firefighter who is also known as "Rakfisk General", who is responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it's not bad - it's reminiscent of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, prior to the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels and then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mostly emigrating to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a complete health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, crossed the border to work.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, albeit fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 € each.
Norway does not often talk about it in international news, which is not to be displeased with.
Here, people are unwilling to talk about Anders Breivik, the racist right-wing extremist who killed 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about "the July 22 incident".
The Norwegians have a hard time accepting that in their peaceful country, one of their own might have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway has owed its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason for our success," says Anna, our waitress, with blond hair and the eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfisk tray in her hand.
We are - how do you say - prudent people.
His English, like most of the people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution – everything, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out of the windows, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep the cords of its stock market tight.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"Without forgetting the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and queue to buy myself something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger composed of momentum, a real discovery, it is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I stay in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where one can vote for the best of them - or perhaps the most odorous of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish, in the Thor-Jürgen mountains?"
"Here are the points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish emanations.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are many.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are rampant in normal times, a security dam has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the goal was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, which is due to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the midst of a drug war that has already killed about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the US president, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A highly populated and sprawling state that encloses the capital. In its land of predilection, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The locals attribute it to the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city, you can take one of the new highways of M Pena Nieto, a major improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of cracks.
Plates bearing his name hang outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are counting on him to put in place lasting change,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a member of the congress and party of Mr Pena Nieto, the PRI.
In terms of security and the economy in particular, we hope for a real change that our country so much needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects criticism from opponents who reproach the new president for lacking in charisma.
He is a whole man, very committed, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image of the people of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more glaring.
Hidden under the highways, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called to the rescue to fight drug gangs in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a disaster zone, the bodies of dozens of women murdered in the past two years have been found on the landfill.
More than 1,000 women have been killed in the state of Mexico while Pena Nieto was governor, a rate far higher than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez - a place infamous for the number of innocent women killed there.
Detractors of Mr. Pena Nieto, say that at best, he failed to stem the problem of murders perpetrated against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to see reality in the face.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version mentions a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed to me that her body had been washed,” says Se<0xC3><0xB1>ora Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the cadaveric rigidity had already begun.
As her mother tells the story, a photo of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross with the word: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family has been refused.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old scoundrel, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want us to accept what they say and be quiet.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has made a promise that he will make it his priority during his term.
“I hope he will be as good as president as he was when he was governor,” Olvera said in Valle del Bravo, a member of Congress.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of abuse, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly a victim of during the detention.
The trial concerns Manning’s detention at a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to dismiss the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors on Friday attempted to demonstrate that Private Bradley Manning — accused of being behind the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history — has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during her nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about her treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a request for the Manning case to be dismissed on the grounds that the abduction took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- came a day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that officers had filled out after meeting Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had given him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had within the prison was "very professional" on the whole.
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would take care of them, but they did not record the issues mentioned.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I didn’t raise any problems,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said it had been assigned this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for its protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know I was okay, and I wanted to be stripped of that status... so I could enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept aware of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, flip flops, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the regulations.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so that they could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he deduced from his guard's order that he had to drop his blanket that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his brief or flip-flops to injure himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he had during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he should be convicted in a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the least serious crimes and fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to national defense.
If all the charges are held, he is liable to life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says Mexico-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of the customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two routes: one for the "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which line to head for.
I grew up in central California, where I've been called the "Mexican" all my life.
This is an ethnic qualifier, just like what my friends in Boston use when they call themselves "Irish," or my friends in New York when they call themselves "Italian."
Then I became “Mexican-American.”
But here it was Mexico.
And on the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualification or line of union.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, good enough to handle an interview in one language or the other.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an indigenous person, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and headed to the "Foreigners" queue.
I thought about that moment of the week when new Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama at the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their preferred themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risking themselves in the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for Trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, although he has not provided further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and filled with bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory in writing at the point of the rifle.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how Americans are undermining the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And the children of Montezuma are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is that the country has with the more than 35 million Mexico-Americans who live in the United States.
Do you want us to talk about bitterness?
There are a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point in our family tree, a person, perhaps a relative or grandparent, did not find any opportunities in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And most often, this person was a typical profile -- dark, uneducated skin from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we are currently living the American dream, that we have gone to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight that it is the American dream that we are living, and not that of Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes troubled, but our loyalty is obvious.
We grant it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that a part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is reciprocal.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they tone us as if we were individuals of inferior strain and not sufficiently Mexican.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we wouldn’t find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but like lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and who legally emigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are frictions between Mexicans and Mexico-Americans, because Mexicans are more firmly claiming their identity and Mexico-Americans are upset by it.
Although she is an American citizen, she feels like she is part of two countries.
On the other hand, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to further complicate the relationship, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and some of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want the Mexican-Americans to work as wealthy ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a superb country that must be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That won't happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, considering the pervasive wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to do it on your own, amigos.
That's okay.
While some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still want them the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old disputes, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such a hope is futile.
While the same futile arguments persist as to who started it, dozens of buildings have been smashed to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in full swing.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet there is every reason to believe that it could help them out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to show optimism.
Even though the ceasefire accorded on November 21 continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has run Gaza since 2007, will boast of forcing Israelis to give up, even if Gaza has been beaten.
Having killed some of its leaders and pushed the 1.7 million people of Gaza into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their Fatah rivals, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken a stand for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Hamas members rejoice and say the Islamist crescent bends around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah militia exercises its dominance, through Syria, where Islamist rebels can overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and as far as Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and most central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to dedicate to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood is a cousin of Hamas, and its leaders are more easily reliant on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important player that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, supporters of Israel’s hard line will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been reinstated.
The missile interception system called Iron Dome has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears – for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America is renewing its unwavering support; and many European countries have accused Hamas of being behind the latest wave of violence.
But more importantly, Israel prospered, notably under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more belligerent party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the beautiful part.
Why pamper these fucking Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they led the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out the head.
Perhaps the supporters of the hard line will prevail; but it may be that the Arab Spring is a game-changer.
Even if Islamists taking power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments settle their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire, which is a good omen -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is doomed to explode one day in Israeli-occupied territories – much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to sound Hamas will have a diplomatic prize.
Both sides need to be pushed by those outside.
The answer remains that advocated by the reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a transfer of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will give outsiders the opportunity to stand up for this cause.
Egypt, which must now try to stop the flow of arms to Gaza, like Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in accordance with the 1967 borders with exchanges of ground and a divided Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute far more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state at the United Nations.
Mr. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This requires a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The laws for neutral cigarette packages have come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of sick organs cover dark green packets that are all identical, regardless of brand
This law came into effect in Australia is a world first, the logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all packages.
It is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous representation.
Studies have shown that if people did not start smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start smoking.
“Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their branding,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that revealed, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the benefits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has pushed against this law.
Tobacco manufacturers said it would revive black market trade, which will make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
“Detrimental consequences will result from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters in China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
