For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living carrying the sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies on contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh in total about 70 kilos, he places them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano which peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall into the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur extracted.
