That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Badminded by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wooden masonry with other bearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulphur does not stop springing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to bearers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive one sous of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) per camera surcharge, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent wearer who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weights of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse of Tamansari, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik said, opening his mouth, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children on the career, stress and cost of accessing property.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these words came from an advertisement for mint lozenges, but despite that, or perhaps because of that, the video spread like a powder trail on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references such as "Let's put a poodle in the drawer" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this advertisement.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to make people “fulfill their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt that this was a topic that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things, like throwing pheromones or holding speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought to ourselves: what could be more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it so lightly.
He spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, in line with its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy for the National Population Division, says it is due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family building,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in place in Singapore last year experienced its worst electoral results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as the "shoe box", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these housing units are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they are not going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off later,” says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
“But for me, it’s important to be able to have my money and my time,” another 20-year-old tells us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons for preventing them from having children.
Thus, while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of private life that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under the age of 16?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, between the ages of 10 and 15, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level with "the password and username" when they applied it to social networks.
“I won’t reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” said Jorge, 10, as he tries to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
“These are very secret secrets, my mother can know them, but not everyone,” he said.
On FB, I post nice pictures or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I’m not going to share one of my photos or someone who would do the stupid thing,” he says.
The young boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they’re responding to me, I’m just posting them,” he added.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly,” he says.
He says he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
He will also not trust someone who would recommend a stranger to him.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people registered on his list of friends.
“I don’t care because we have something in common, music for example,” he said.
According to the boy, no one gave him advances or asked him for his address or phone number.
“If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account,” he acknowledges.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A close friend of mine was bullied on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He only passed it on to a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I were angry or angry.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information, but with the appearance of these sites, the rule of the game has changed,” she said.
Porras notes that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
It is the digital natives, children and young people, who were born with technology.
“We, we’re the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we’re learning ourselves,” she says.
He adds that the topic is complex, "because we ask them to have a definite criterion as to what is or is not appropriate to disclose, publish or say at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she added.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents privacy is to use questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it is useless,” she says.
Next, Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to post a picture of you like a friend you posted?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you’re doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
“Besides the Internet, everyone has to act with respect, morality and other principles, it has to be the same on social media,” she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education adviser, says it is essential for parents to read conscientiously the conditions of use of social networks.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation to discuss with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to foreigners.
UNASUR Summit ended without Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the summit closed, and then claimed that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exposed by Peru’s President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the newsroom.
The little information that circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the Unasur governments who were attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the “final statement” of the summit, but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was urged by the press, it had not disseminated the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published in March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited to the maximum the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that decides a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both sides in the Lima trial against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and enforce the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing today before this international court,” Humala said in a statement.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals,” President Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era said, shaking hands with President Humala, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was instructed to open the deliberations in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He said that actions would be put in place to improve “cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better accessibility of medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters.”
With a Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalistic matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to foresee a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," he said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow it to re-integrate into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” President Santos said.
“We will review all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with that country,” he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to witness the takeover of the new president of the country, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Plan of Action, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
“South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship,” says Rafael Correa.
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship was a goal for which "South America, in this case, should take an example from Europe".
President Correa, who participated in the Sixth Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), located in Lima, told state television, TV Peru, that Europeans "were killed during World War II" and during other conflicts, "but they now formed almost a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the project to establish South American citizenship encouraged by the Unasur member countries.
“We must achieve the free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case for members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make belong to the past,” he warned.
In addition, the Ecuadorian president supported the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of diminishing the influence of Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on human rights.
Those who beat our ears never compromise anything, conversely, we South Americans have all signed it.
“It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under US funding,” he said, referring to Ecuador’s political asylum granted to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa says he does not regret his decision, because he did not betray his own principles, but instead respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He concluded that at the time, “there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected.”
In addition, he criticizes the Swedish justice system, which has demanded that he submit to an interrogation on his territory concerning a suspected sexual offence while "Swedish legislation itself allows for this to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London."
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's mental and physical health would deteriorate.
“I haven’t spoken to him since he was in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, but nothing serious,” he said.
It is possible that his physical and mental health may be deteriorated by being locked up in a small space without being able to exercise in the open air.
“It affects anyone’s health,” he concludes.
Correa notes that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the allocation of a safe-conduct that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities and he points out that he had discussions in London to find a solution to the hell.
We are not negotiating with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been ongoing discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a whole series of proceedings with different European authorities," he said.
And he believes that “if Britain granted safe driving tomorrow, it would be over.”
And if Sweden, as its legislation fully allows, and as it has already done in other cases, questioned Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or questioned him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was “mediocrity, bad faith and lies that undermine freedom of expression.”
“The greatest enemies of press freedom are not evil or perverse politicians but bad journalists for greed, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
From this point of view, he congratulated himself that it was not this kind of journalist "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries dominating Ecuador" and, rather than promoting his re-election, "it would deepen the revolution to continue the way and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay within the Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality "it destroys the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
It is necessary to solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the sound resolution of the dispute over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile in the same tribunal and said that it is "beneficial for Latin America to refer to international fora if the two countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it is".
Referring to the eventuality of his candidacy as a candidate in the future presidential elections in Ecuador, in order to run for a third consecutive term, he pointed out that he saw this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primary, he would retire from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed it was I who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we must accept that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last presidential term and then I will retire from politics.
If we ever lose, I will, too.
“It’s my decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just talked to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse of President Chávez's health condition," he said.
The Ecuadorian Head of State participated today in Lima at the Sixth Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), which ended with a call for better regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed with the HIV-positive test.
"It's as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful," in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to find out about him and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmata.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HCG HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as reference that this information was validated in a scientific publication in April of this year.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depended on the level of immune system affection that patients presented at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs: up to a rate of 50' for 30 years.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who would be diagnosed positively with HIV at age 25, “as long as they remain under control, they will be able to live without problems up to 75 years of age,” he said.
In order to put this progress in context, it must be noted that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS has increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I think the problem does not come from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never lacked any medications, the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it in advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all people who request it.”
The specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS, who suffered from complications of the cancer of Kapicom.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to know.
“If I’m going to die, it’s better that I break up three times a week,” they say, “that’s not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To this day, his parents only know that he suffers from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of the World AIDS Day.
If they do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who has embraced the cause of HIV.
The biggest issue is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, it is very good, but the result, even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", posed with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
He proposed redirecting this ineffective distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
This is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, it’s best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 for AIDS and 1,317 for HIV).
The State is the 4th state in the country in the number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexual, 6% are bloodborne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for each recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who are unaware of it.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, and the scenario creates a detrimental precedent for all domestic companies with ramifications in the neighboring country and with solvency problems.
Thus, it seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the star-flagged country, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the June 15 ruling by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of an embargo on their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s top glass manufacturer to sue the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the trial judge points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans says the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
