Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globetrotter of basketball "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, has traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of the history of local basketball as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, a manager and a national team leader, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as a football president.
"I have worn several hats in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball is my whole life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his extraordinary itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves the most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
“It’s been my best years, the ones I’ve enjoyed the most because I’ve had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967 onwards, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
It's been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired at the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great director, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a manager here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, "I have a tough player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
This is how to start with Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was pleased with the championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's duties in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we were 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn’t made us play the last game again, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat up the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the World Cup of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that may not be the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the suspended players by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we have won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, this is Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n did.
And that without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
What is your biggest success in the federation?
To have been one of the most glorious times of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have liked to have put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the boys from Ponce only play in their area and only play teams from other corners of the island in the national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of compulsory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch clips from my time on YouTube, I enjoy my grandchildren, and from time to time I watch basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas."
“Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved the most again,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on that Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press secretary Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had become known on television as an ordinary guy in the NBC television series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critically-received roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", coined to keep the suspense going around an emotional episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has spawned speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment show in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had garnered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
“I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R.,” Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as a "huge man, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who have been fortunate enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
Recording of five episodes has already been completed for the second season and a sixth is in the works, the channel said.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated about how Hagman's death will be incorporated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who gained fame with classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his first steps on the stage of New York theatres in the early 1950s and served in the air force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoir Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
“I haven’t written anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way,” he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist worried patients.
"I advise them, I give them confidence, I come with them when they come to have surgery and then," he said in 1996.
I’m trying to offer them some comfort, like, “Don’t be afraid, it won’t be easy for a little while, but it’ll be fine.”
He has also been an anti-smoking activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charme decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing there an irresistible hook: the end of the "great count" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmed had no idea what to expect over the next few months: catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a tax chasm that some have dubbed the “Debt Armageddon,” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-day Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would unleash.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Professor Charmed told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we tell it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give classes on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled “The End of the World.”
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” Professor Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have proven to be quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received email messages several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students questioned, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end of the world date of December 21.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old senior from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, dating back centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in these speculations.
“In other places around the world, people don’t think about that,” he says.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded promptly when asked if he knew we were giving classes here on "the end of the world."
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he said, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, there has been talk of the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment, and he claims that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they thought they would go to "end of the world" parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
